The [event](https://docs.substrate.io/main-docs/build/events-errors/) emitted
			by this pallet.

members.name: Attempted
docs: Execution of an XCM message was attempted.
\[ outcome \]

members.name: Sent
docs: A XCM message was sent.
\[ origin, destination, message \]

members.name: UnexpectedResponse
docs: Query response received which does not match a registered query. This may be because a
matching query was never registered, it may be because it is a duplicate response, or
because the query timed out.
\[ origin location, id \]

members.name: ResponseReady
docs: Query response has been received and is ready for taking with `take_response`. There is
no registered notification call.
\[ id, response \]

members.name: Notified
docs: Query response has been received and query is removed. The registered notification has
been dispatched and executed successfully.
\[ id, pallet index, call index \]

members.name: NotifyOverweight
docs: Query response has been received and query is removed. The registered notification could
not be dispatched because the dispatch weight is greater than the maximum weight
originally budgeted by this runtime for the query result.
\[ id, pallet index, call index, actual weight, max budgeted weight \]

members.name: NotifyDispatchError
docs: Query response has been received and query is removed. There was a general error with
dispatching the notification call.
\[ id, pallet index, call index \]

members.name: NotifyDecodeFailed
docs: Query response has been received and query is removed. The dispatch was unable to be
decoded into a `Call`; this might be due to dispatch function having a signature which
is not `(origin, QueryId, Response)`.
\[ id, pallet index, call index \]

members.name: InvalidResponder
docs: Expected query response has been received but the origin location of the response does
not match that expected. The query remains registered for a later, valid, response to
be received and acted upon.
\[ origin location, id, expected location \]

members.name: InvalidResponderVersion
docs: Expected query response has been received but the expected origin location placed in
storage by this runtime previously cannot be decoded. The query remains registered.
This is unexpected (since a location placed in storage in a previously executing
runtime should be readable prior to query timeout) and dangerous since the possibly
valid response will be dropped. Manual governance intervention is probably going to be
needed.
\[ origin location, id \]

members.name: ResponseTaken
docs: Received query response has been read and removed.

members.name: AssetsTrapped
docs: Some assets have been placed in an asset trap.
\[ hash, origin, assets \]

members.name: VersionChangeNotified
docs: An XCM version change notification message has been attempted to be sent.
The cost of sending it (borne by the chain) is included.
\[ destination, result, cost \]

members.name: SupportedVersionChanged
docs: The supported version of a location has been changed. This might be through an
automatic notification or a manual intervention.
\[ location, XCM version \]

members.name: NotifyTargetSendFail
docs: A given location which had a version change subscription was dropped owing to an error
sending the notification to it.
\[ location, query ID, error \]

members.name: NotifyTargetMigrationFail
docs: A given location which had a version change subscription was dropped owing to an error
migrating the location to our new XCM format.
\[ location, query ID \]

members.name: InvalidQuerierVersion
docs: Expected query response has been received but the expected querier location placed in
storage by this runtime previously cannot be decoded. The query remains registered.
This is unexpected (since a location placed in storage in a previously executing
runtime should be readable prior to query timeout) and dangerous since the possibly
valid response will be dropped. Manual governance intervention is probably going to be
needed.
\[ origin location, id \]

members.name: InvalidQuerier
docs: Expected query response has been received but the querier location of the response does
not match the expected. The query remains registered for a later, valid, response to
be received and acted upon.
\[ origin location, id, expected querier, maybe actual querier \]

members.name: VersionNotifyStarted
docs: A remote has requested XCM version change notification from us and we have honored it.
A version information message is sent to them and its cost is included.
\[ destination location, cost \]

members.name: VersionNotifyRequested
docs: We have requested that a remote chain sends us XCM version change notifications.
\[ destination location, cost \]

members.name: VersionNotifyUnrequested
docs: We have requested that a remote chain stops sending us XCM version change notifications.
\[ destination location, cost \]

members.name: FeesPaid

docs: Events deposited for the current block.
NOTE: The item is unbound and should therefore never be read on chain.

Events have a large in-memory size. Box the events to not go out-of-memory
just in case someone still reads them from within the runtime.

entries.name: EventTopics
docs: Mapping between a topic (represented by T::Hash) and a vector of indexes
of events in the `<Events<T>>` list.
All topic vectors have deterministic storage locations depending on the topic. This
allows light-clients to leverage the changes trie storage tracking mechanism and
in case of changes fetch the list of events of interest.
The value has the type `(T::BlockNumber, EventIndex)` because if we used only just
the `EventIndex` then in case if the topic has the same contents on the next block
no notification will be triggered thus the event might be lost.

entries.name: Account
docs: The Balances pallet example of storing the balance of an account.
# Example
```nocompile
impl pallet_balances::Config for Runtime {
type AccountStore = StorageMapShim<Self::Account<Runtime>, frame_system::Provider<Runtime>, AccountId, Self::AccountData<Balance>>
You can also store the balance of an account in the `System` pallet.
# Example
```nocompile
impl pallet_balances::Config for Runtime {
type AccountStore = System
But this comes with tradeoffs, storing account balances in the system pallet stores
`frame_system` data alongside the account data contrary to storing account balances in the
`Balances` pallet, which uses a `StorageMap` to store balances data only.
NOTE: This is only used in the case that this pallet is used to store balances.

constants.name: ExistentialDeposit

If you *really* need it to be zero, you can enable the feature `insecure_zero_ed` for
this pallet. However, you do so at your own risk: this will open up a major DoS vector.
In case you have multiple sources of provider references, you may also get unexpected
behaviour if you set this to zero.
Bottom line: Do yourself a favour and make it at least one!

constants.name: OperationalFeeMultiplier
docs: A fee mulitplier for `Operational` extrinsics to compute "virtual tip" to boost their
`priority`
This value is multipled by the `final_fee` to obtain a "virtual tip" that is later
added to a tip component in regular `priority` calculations.
It means that a `Normal` transaction can front-run a similarly-sized `Operational`
extrinsic (with no tip), by including a tip value greater than the virtual tip.
```rust,ignore
// For `Normal`
let priority = priority_calc(tip);
// For `Operational`
let virtual_tip = (inclusion_fee + tip) * OperationalFeeMultiplier;
let priority = priority_calc(tip + virtual_tip);
Note that since we use `final_fee` the multiplier applies also to the regular `tip`
sent with the transaction. So, not only does the transaction get a priority bump based
on the `inclusion_fee`, but we also amplify the impact of tips applied to `Operational`
transactions.

entries.name: DepositOf
docs: Those who have locked a deposit.
TWOX-NOTE: Safe, as increasing integer keys are safe.

entries.name: ReferendumCount
docs: The next free referendum index, aka the number of referenda started so far.

entries.name: LowestUnbaked
docs: The lowest referendum index representing an unbaked referendum. Equal to
`ReferendumCount` if there isn't a unbaked referendum.

entries.name: ReferendumInfoOf
docs: Information concerning any given referendum.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE as indexes are not under an attackers control.

entries.name: VotingOf
docs: All votes for a particular voter. We store the balance for the number of votes that we
have recorded. The second item is the total amount of delegations, that will be added.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE as `AccountId`s are crypto hashes anyway.

entries.name: LastTabledWasExternal
docs: True if the last referendum tabled was submitted externally. False if it was a public
proposal.

entries.name: NextExternal
docs: The referendum to be tabled whenever it would be valid to table an external proposal.
This happens when a referendum needs to be tabled and one of two conditions are met:
- `LastTabledWasExternal` is `false`; or
- `PublicProps` is empty.

entries.name: Blacklist
docs: A record of who vetoed what. Maps proposal hash to a possible existent block number
(until when it may not be resubmitted) and who vetoed it.

entries.name: Cancellations
docs: Record of all proposals that have been subject to emergency cancellation.

entries.name: MetadataOf
docs: General information concerning any proposal or referendum.
The `PreimageHash` refers to the preimage of the `Preimages` provider which can be a JSON
dump or IPFS hash of a JSON file.
Consider a garbage collection for a metadata of finished referendums to `unrequest` (remove)
large preimages.

constants.name: EnactmentPeriod
docs: The period between a proposal being approved and enacted.
It should generally be a little more than the unstake period to ensure that
voting stakers have an opportunity to remove themselves from the system in the case
where they are on the losing side of a vote.

constants.name: LaunchPeriod
docs: How often (in blocks) new public referenda are launched.

constants.name: VotingPeriod
docs: How often (in blocks) to check for new votes.

constants.name: VoteLockingPeriod
docs: The minimum period of vote locking.
It should be no shorter than enactment period to ensure that in the case of an approval,
those successful voters are locked into the consequences that their votes entail.

constants.name: MinimumDeposit
docs: The minimum amount to be used as a deposit for a public referendum proposal.

constants.name: InstantAllowed
docs: Indicator for whether an emergency origin is even allowed to happen. Some chains may
want to set this permanently to `false`, others may want to condition it on things such
as an upgrade having happened recently.

constants.name: FastTrackVotingPeriod
docs: Minimum voting period allowed for a fast-track referendum.

constants.name: CooloffPeriod
docs: Period in blocks where an external proposal may not be re-submitted after being vetoed.

constants.name: MaxVotes
docs: The maximum number of votes for an account.
Also used to compute weight, an overly big value can
lead to extrinsic with very big weight: see `delegate` for instance.

constants.name: MaxProposals
docs: The maximum number of public proposals that can exist at any time.

constants.name: MaxDeposits
docs: The maximum number of deposits a public proposal may have at any time.

constants.name: MaxBlacklisted
docs: The maximum number of items which can be blacklisted.

entries.name: StatusFor
docs: The request status of a given hash.

entries.name: VotingFor
docs: All voting for a particular voter in a particular voting class. We store the balance for the
number of votes that we have recorded.

entries.name: ClassLocksFor
docs: The voting classes which have a non-zero lock requirement and the lock amounts which they
require. The actual amount locked on behalf of this pallet should always be the maximum of
this list.

constants.name: MaxVotes
docs: The maximum number of concurrent votes an account may have.
Also used to compute weight, an overly large value can lead to extrinsics with large
weight estimation: see `delegate` for instance.

constants.name: VoteLockingPeriod
docs: The minimum period of vote locking.
It should be no shorter than enactment period to ensure that in the case of an approval,
those successful voters are locked into the consequences that their votes entail.

entries.name: ReferendumCount
docs: The next free referendum index, aka the number of referenda started so far.

entries.name: ReferendumInfoFor
docs: Information concerning any given referendum.

entries.name: TrackQueue
docs: The sorted list of referenda ready to be decided but not yet being decided, ordered by
conviction-weighted approvals.
This should be empty if `DecidingCount` is less than `TrackInfo::max_deciding`.

entries.name: DecidingCount
docs: The number of referenda being decided currently.

entries.name: MetadataOf
docs: The metadata is a general information concerning the referendum.
The `PreimageHash` refers to the preimage of the `Preimages` provider which can be a JSON
dump or IPFS hash of a JSON file.
Consider a garbage collection for a metadata of finished referendums to `unrequest` (remove)
large preimages.

constants.name: SubmissionDeposit
docs: The minimum amount to be used as a deposit for a public referendum proposal.

constants.name: MaxQueued
docs: Maximum size of the referendum queue for a single track.

constants.name: UndecidingTimeout
docs: The number of blocks after submission that a referendum must begin being decided by.
Once this passes, then anyone may cancel the referendum.

constants.name: AlarmInterval
docs: Quantization level for the referendum wakeup scheduler. A higher number will result in
fewer storage reads/writes needed for smaller voters, but also result in delays to the
automatic referendum status changes. Explicit servicing instructions are unaffected.

constants.name: Tracks
docs: Information concerning the different referendum tracks.

entries.name: Proposals
docs: The hashes of the active proposals.

entries.name: ProposalOf
docs: Actual proposal for a given hash, if it's current.

entries.name: Voting
docs: Votes on a given proposal, if it is ongoing.

entries.name: ProposalCount
docs: Proposals so far.

entries.name: Members
docs: The current members of the collective. This is stored sorted (just by value).

entries.name: Prime
docs: The prime member that helps determine the default vote behavior in case of absentations.

constants.name: MaxProposalWeight
docs: The maximum weight of a dispatch call that can be proposed and executed.

entries.name: ProposalCount
docs: Number of proposals that have been made.

entries.name: Proposals
docs: Proposals that have been made.

entries.name: Deactivated
docs: The amount which has been reported as inactive to Currency.

entries.name: Approvals
docs: Proposal indices that have been approved but not yet awarded.

constants.name: ProposalBond
docs: Fraction of a proposal's value that should be bonded in order to place the proposal.
An accepted proposal gets these back. A rejected proposal does not.

constants.name: ProposalBondMinimum
docs: Minimum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: ProposalBondMaximum
docs: Maximum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: SpendPeriod
docs: Period between successive spends.

constants.name: Burn
docs: Percentage of spare funds (if any) that are burnt per spend period.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: The treasury's pallet id, used for deriving its sovereign account ID.

constants.name: MaxApprovals
docs: The maximum number of approvals that can wait in the spending queue.
NOTE: This parameter is also used within the Bounties Pallet extension if enabled.

entries.name: InitRelayBlock
docs: Vesting block height at the initialization of the pallet

entries.name: EndRelayBlock
docs: Vesting block height at the initialization of the pallet

entries.name: InitializedRewardAmount
docs: Total initialized amount so far. We store this to make pallet funds == contributors reward
check easier and more efficient

entries.name: TotalContributors
docs: Total number of contributors to aid hinting benchmarking

constants.name: InitializationPayment
docs: Percentage to be payed at initialization

constants.name: RewardAddressRelayVoteThreshold
docs: A fraction representing the percentage of proofs
that need to be presented to change a reward address through the relay keys

constants.name: SignatureNetworkIdentifier
docs: Network Identifier to be appended into the signatures for reward address change/association
Prevents replay attacks from one network to the other

entries.name: InboundXcmpStatus
docs: Status of the inbound XCMP channels.

entries.name: InboundXcmpMessages
docs: Inbound aggregate XCMP messages. It can only be one per ParaId/block.

entries.name: OutboundXcmpStatus
docs: The non-empty XCMP channels in order of becoming non-empty, and the index of the first
and last outbound message. If the two indices are equal, then it indicates an empty
queue and there must be a non-`Ok` `OutboundStatus`. We assume queues grow no greater
than 65535 items. Queue indices for normal messages begin at one; zero is reserved in
case of the need to send a high-priority signal message this block.
The bool is true if there is a signal message waiting to be sent.

entries.name: OutboundXcmpMessages
docs: The messages outbound in a given XCMP channel.

entries.name: SignalMessages
docs: Any signal messages waiting to be sent.

entries.name: QueueConfig
docs: The configuration which controls the dynamics of the outbound queue.

entries.name: Overweight
docs: The messages that exceeded max individual message weight budget.
These message stay in this storage map until they are manually dispatched via
`service_overweight`.

entries.name: CounterForOverweight
docs: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: OverweightCount
docs: The number of overweight messages ever recorded in `Overweight`. Also doubles as the next
available free overweight index.

entries.name: QueueSuspended
docs: Whether or not the XCMP queue is suspended from executing incoming XCMs or not.

entries.name: Configuration
docs: The configuration.

entries.name: PageIndex
docs: The page index.

entries.name: Pages
docs: The queue pages.

entries.name: Overweight
docs: The overweight messages.

entries.name: CounterForOverweight
docs: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: QueryCounter
docs: The latest available query index.

entries.name: Queries
docs: The ongoing queries.

entries.name: AssetTraps
docs: The existing asset traps.
Key is the blake2 256 hash of (origin, versioned `MultiAssets`) pair. Value is the number of
times this pair has been trapped (usually just 1 if it exists at all).

entries.name: SafeXcmVersion
docs: Default version to encode XCM when latest version of destination is unknown. If `None`,
then the destinations whose XCM version is unknown are considered unreachable.

entries.name: SupportedVersion
docs: The Latest versions that we know various locations support.

entries.name: VersionNotifiers
docs: All locations that we have requested version notifications from.

entries.name: VersionNotifyTargets
docs: The target locations that are subscribed to our version changes, as well as the most recent
of our versions we informed them of.

entries.name: VersionDiscoveryQueue
docs: Destinations whose latest XCM version we would like to know. Duplicates not allowed, and
the `u32` counter is the number of times that a send to the destination has been attempted,
which is used as a prioritization.

entries.name: CurrentMigration
docs: The current migration's stage, if any.

entries.name: RemoteLockedFungibles
docs: Fungible assets which we know are locked on a remote chain.

entries.name: LockedFungibles
docs: Fungible assets which we know are locked on this chain.

entries.name: XcmExecutionSuspended
docs: Global suspension state of the XCM executor.

entries.name: Asset
docs: Details of an asset.

entries.name: Account
docs: The holdings of a specific account for a specific asset.

entries.name: Approvals
docs: Approved balance transfers. First balance is the amount approved for transfer. Second
is the amount of `T::Currency` reserved for storing this.
First key is the asset ID, second key is the owner and third key is the delegate.

entries.name: Metadata
docs: Metadata of an asset.

constants.name: RemoveItemsLimit
docs: Max number of items to destroy per `destroy_accounts` and `destroy_approvals` call.
Must be configured to result in a weight that makes each call fit in a block.

constants.name: AssetDeposit
docs: The basic amount of funds that must be reserved for an asset.

constants.name: AssetAccountDeposit
docs: The amount of funds that must be reserved for a non-provider asset account to be
maintained.

constants.name: MetadataDepositBase
docs: The basic amount of funds that must be reserved when adding metadata to your asset.

constants.name: MetadataDepositPerByte
docs: The additional funds that must be reserved for the number of bytes you store in your
metadata.

constants.name: ApprovalDeposit
docs: The amount of funds that must be reserved when creating a new approval.

constants.name: StringLimit
docs: The maximum length of a name or symbol stored on-chain.

entries.name: AssetIdType
docs: Mapping from an asset id to asset type.
This is mostly used when receiving transaction specifying an asset directly,
like transferring an asset from this chain to another.

entries.name: AssetTypeId
docs: Reverse mapping of AssetIdType. Mapping from an asset type to an asset id.
This is mostly used when receiving a multilocation XCM message to retrieve
the corresponding asset in which tokens should me minted.

entries.name: AssetTypeUnitsPerSecond
docs: Stores the units per second for local execution for a AssetType.
This is used to know how to charge for XCM execution in a particular
asset
Not all assets might contain units per second, hence the different storage

entries.name: LocalAssetCounter
docs: Stores the counter of the number of local assets that have been
created so far
This value can be used to salt the creation of an assetId, e.g.,
by hashing it. This is particularly useful for cases like moonbeam
where letting users choose their assetId would result in collision
in the evm side.

entries.name: LocalAssetDeposit
docs: Local asset deposits, a mapping from assetId to a struct
holding the creator (from which the deposit was reserved) and
the deposit amount

constants.name: LocalAssetDeposit
docs: The basic amount of funds that must be reserved for a local asset.

constants.name: SelfLocation
docs: Self chain location.

constants.name: BaseXcmWeight
docs: Base XCM weight.
The actually weight for an XCM message is `T::BaseXcmWeight +
T::Weigher::weight(&msg)`.

entries.name: IndexToAccount
docs: Since we are using pallet-utility for account derivation (through AsDerivative),
we need to provide an index for the account derivation. This storage item stores the index
assigned for a given local account. These indices are usable as derivative in the relay chain

entries.name: TransactInfoWithWeightLimit
docs: Stores the transact info of a MultiLocation. This defines how much extra weight we need to
add when we want to transact in the destination chain and maximum amount of weight allowed
by the destination chain

entries.name: DestinationAssetFeePerSecond
docs: Stores the fee per second for an asset in its reserve chain. This allows us to convert
from weight to fee

constants.name: SelfLocation
docs: Self chain location.

docs: The actual weight for an XCM message is `T::BaseXcmWeight +
T::Weigher::weight(&msg)`.

entries.name: Nonce
docs: Global nonce used for building Ethereum transaction payload.

entries.name: EthereumXcmSuspended
docs: Whether or not Ethereum-XCM is suspended from executing

entries.name: Requests
docs: Randomness requests not yet fulfilled or purged

entries.name: RequestCount
docs: Number of randomness requests made so far, used to generate the next request's uid

entries.name: LocalVrfOutput
docs: Current local per-block VRF randomness
Set in `on_initialize`

entries.name: RelayEpoch
docs: Relay epoch

entries.name: InherentIncluded
docs: Ensures the mandatory inherent was included in the block

entries.name: NotFirstBlock
docs: Records whether this is the first block (genesis or runtime upgrade)

entries.name: RandomnessResults
docs: Snapshot of randomness to fulfill all requests that are for the same raw randomness
Removed once $value.request_count == 0

entries.name: PreviousLocalVrfOutput
docs: Previous local per-block VRF randomness
Set in `on_finalize` of last block

constants.name: Deposit
docs: The amount that should be taken as a security deposit when requesting randomness.

constants.name: MaxRandomWords
docs: Maximum number of random words that can be requested per request

constants.name: MinBlockDelay
docs: Local per-block VRF requests must be at least this many blocks after the block in which
they were requested

constants.name: MaxBlockDelay
docs: Local per-block VRF requests must be at most this many blocks after the block in which
they were requested

constants.name: BlockExpirationDelay
docs: Local requests expire and can be purged from storage after this many blocks/epochs

constants.name: EpochExpirationDelay
docs: Babe requests expire and can be purged from storage after this many blocks/epochs
